{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "'Entities' usually include named entities (people, organizations, locations), or meaningful concepts known to an existing knowledge base.",
    "The earliest of such approaches is Jigsaw [49], where entities are linked if they appear in the same document.",
    "FacetAtlas [14] generalizes the idea of entity to 'facets' which can be entities or any keywords or user's interest.",
    "ConceptVector [43] uses 'concept' to represent a similar idea.",
    "Generally, entity-based approaches exhibit better model alignments than topic-based approaches [18], but the polysemy of natural language makes them prone to produce false positives [43]."
  ],
